Here=E2=80=99s the key point: if Nvidia demand exceeds supply then the comp=
any=E2=80=99s sales are, in some respect, controlled by Nvidia=E2=80=99s su=
ppliers, from TSMC on down. Now that=E2=80=99s not completely true, because=
 Nvidia can raise its prices, and it appears they did just that: the compan=
y achieved its highest gross margins ever, and forecasted the same thing th=
is quarter. That, though, only accentuates the fact that the company is sup=
ply-constrained in a world of astronomical demand.

This remains, by-and-large, the best way to look at Nvidia=E2=80=99s earnin=
gs; the company regularly beats its guidance =E2=80=94 which (note the date=
) are always delivered pretty late in the quarter =E2=80=94 by about $2 bil=
lion. The biggest change this quarter is that Wall Street is catching up to=
 the game and modeling its expectations to account for this. Why, though, c=
an Nvidia be so regular? The most obvious answer is what I wrote last Febru=
ary: the company is gated by supply, which is much easier to model than dem=
and.

To that end, Doug O=E2=80=99Laughlin at Fabricated Knowledge ( https://www.=
fabricatedknowledge.com/p/nvidia-waiting-on-blackwell-and-whats ) noted tha=
t Wall Street=E2=80=99s understanding of Nvidia reminded him of Apple and t=
he iPhone:

Lower-than-expected beats mean the street is finally catching up to Nvidia,=
 which is good thing. It=E2=80=99s the largest company in the world, and it=
 shouldn=E2=80=99t be possible to see 20% revenue beats without the whole w=
orld knowing. The reality is the bigger you are, the less volatile your res=
ults. The bigger you are, the more flows it takes to move your stock, and a=
s you become a larger company, the +/- 20% moves usually start to simmer do=
wn. There=E2=80=99s an excellent historical analogy to this: the iPhone. On=
ce upon a time, Apple had massive revenue beats similar (but nowhere near a=
s big!) to what you=E2=80=99re seeing today when they launched the iPhone. =
That surprise has gotten smaller over time.

Apple's increasingly predictable revenue growth ( https://www.fabricatedkno=
wledge.com/p/nvidia-waiting-on-blackwell-and-whats )

It=E2=80=99s also easier to get wind of your supply chain. I think that tod=
ay=E2=80=99s earnings result was quite dull, and the reality is that=E2=80=
=99s a good thing. Boring execution is alright, and Nvidia is doing that wi=
th 90% revenue growth year over year.

I agree with O=E2=80=99Laughlin, but would make a further iPhone analogy. W=
hile O=E2=80=99Laughlin is focused on the market=E2=80=99s understanding of=
 Nvidia and comparing that to the iPhone, I think the analogy also applies =
to the relevant companies=E2=80=99 own understanding of their markets. I wr=
ote in an April 2016 Update ( https://stratechery.com/2016/apples-run-apple=
