esults:

I know I=E2=80=99m kind of harping on this point, but in fact I find any po=
ssible explanation for this inconsistency very troubling: either Cook was p=
urposely overselling the upgrade narrative last year, which would not only =
be duplicitous but also dumb, given that he would only be setting up Apple =
for a fall this cycle; or even as late as last year Cook was out of touch w=
ith how the iPhone upgrade cycle actually works, or how it may have changed=
 over time.

I strongly suspect it is the latter explanation, and while that is concerni=
ng, it=E2=80=99s also understandable; the implication of my ongoing content=
ion that the iPhone has now picked all of the =E2=80=9Clow-hanging fruit=E2=
=80=9D of growth is that iPhone growth had multiple causes: certainly the i=
nherent quality and new features of each annual iPhone model played a role,=
 but an arguably bigger factor was simply distribution =E2=80=94 getting th=
e iPhone onto more carriers in more countries. Indeed, I strongly suspect t=
he predictable impact of increased distribution helps explain why Apple=E2=
=80=99s earnings forecasts were so eerily accurate for so many years.

Apple, though, has been a lot less accurate for the last five quarters: the=
 iPhone 6 sold better than they expected in nearly every quarter, and now t=
he iPhone 6S is selling worse (note the Maestri forecast errors I highlight=
ed above); along similar lines, Apple seems to have underestimated iPhone S=
E demand to a significant degree. Ultimately, while I think Apple still has=
 the advantage when it comes selling people their second (or third or nth) =
smartphones, what I think we are seeing is that it=E2=80=99s a lot more dif=
ficult to determine when exactly that sale will occur, and Apple itself is =
only now coming to grips with that.

There is no better time to be a forecaster than when demand exceed supply, =
because supply is more easily understandable and predictable; Apple=E2=80=
=99s forecasters for the first eight or so years of the iPhone weren=E2=80=
=99t geniuses, they just understood that as Apple brought the iPhone to new=
 carriers, complete with guaranteed sales contracts, they knew to a high de=
gree of accuracy how many iPhones they would sell. The moment that iPhones =
were available everywhere, however, was the moment that Apple=E2=80=99s for=
ecasting accuracy plummeted.

What is interesting about the coming quarter is the transition to Blackwell=
, which is the first Nvidia chip truly designed for the transformer-based w=
orkloads that undergird generative AI. Demand is, unsurprisingly, far in ex=
cess of supply. CFO Colette Kress said on the earnings call ( https://seeki=
ngalpha.com/article/4739171-nvidia-corporation-nvda-q3-2025-earnings-call-t=
ranscript ) :

Total revenue is expected to be $37.5 billion, plus or minus 2%, which inco=
rporates continued demand for Hopper architecture and the initial ramp of o=
ur Blackwell products, while demand is greatly exceed supply, we are on tra=
ck to exceed our previous Blackwell revenue estimate of several billion dol=
lars as our visibility into supply continues to increase.

It=E2=80=99s the Hopper part that=E2=80=99s interesting; how many companies=
 want to buy the previous top-of-the-line GPU, and for how long? Kress admi=
tted that the company was uncertain:

The second statement was a question regarding our Hopper and what is our Ho=
pper doing. We have seen substantial growth for our H200, not only in terms=
 of orders but the quickness in terms of those that are standing that up. I=
t is an amazing product and it=E2=80=99s the fastest-growing and ramping th=
at we=E2=80=99ve seen. We will continue to be selling Hopper in this quarte=
r, in Q4 for sure, that is across-the-board in terms of all of our differen=
t configurations and our configurations include what we may do in terms of =
China. But keep that in mind that folks are also at the same time looking t=
o build out their Blackwell. So we=E2=80=99ve got a little bit of both happ=
ening in Q4. But yes, is it possible for Hopper to grow between Q3 and Q4, =
it=E2=80=99s possible, but we=E2=80=99ll just have to see.

In that February 2024 Update I excerpted above, I highlighted how Huang (ac=
curately) noted ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/4695145-nvidia-corporati=
on-nvda-q1-2025-earnings-call-transcript ) that the announcement of Blackwe=
ll wouldn=E2=80=99t impact Hopper sales because companies had a huge incent=
ive to train new models now:

Let me give you an example of time being really valuable, why this idea of =
standing up a data center instantaneously is so valuable and getting this t=
hing called time to train is so valuable. The reason for that is because th=
e next company who reaches the next major plateau gets to announce a ground=
breaking AI. And the second one after that gets to announce something that=
=E2=80=99s 0.3% better. And so the question is, do you want to be repeatedl=
y the company delivering groundbreaking AI or the company delivering 0.3% b=
etter? And that=E2=80=99s the reason why this race, as in all technology ra=
ces, the race is so important. And you=E2=80=99re seeing this race across m=
ultiple companies because this is so vital to have technology leadership, f=
or companies to trust the leadership and want to build on your platform and=
 know that the platform that they=E2=80=99re building on is going to get be=
tter and better. And so leadership matters a great deal. Time to train matt=
ers a great deal. The difference between time to train that is three months=
 earlier just to get it done, in order to get time to train on three-months=
 project, getting started three months earlier is everything. And so it=E2=
=80=99s the reason why we=E2=80=99re standing up Hopper systems like mad ri=
ght now because the next plateau is just around the corner.

An example of this point is the H100 cluster that xAI just set up. That not=
ed, it certainly does seem like the plateau arrived; GPT-4 class models con=
tinue to improve, but there hasn=E2=80=99t yet been a GPT-5 class model. To=
 that end, I would expect that training-focused workloads will be built aro=
und Blackwell going forward; that means that the question is how many compa=
nies will buy Hoppers for inference while Blackwells are in short supply. T=
hat in turns highlights what was not in this call: for the last three quart=
