Strawberry and Video
--------------------

Of course that raises the question about training and whether or not scalin=
g laws still hold. Huang was asked about this explicitly and (of course) sa=
id yes:

*I guess just a question for you on the debate around whether scaling for l=
arge language models have stalled. Obviously, we=E2=80=99re very early here=
 but would love to hear your thoughts on this front. How are you helping yo=
ur customers as they work through these issues? And then obviously, part of=
 the context here as we=E2=80=99re discussing clusters that have yet to ben=
efit from Blackwell. So is this driving even greater demand for Blackwell?*

*JH:* A foundation model pre-training scaling is intact and it=E2=80=99s co=
ntinuing. As you know, this is an empirical law, not a fundamental physical=
 law, but the evidence is that it continues to scale. What we=E2=80=99re le=
arning, however, is that it=E2=80=99s not enough that we=E2=80=99ve now dis=
covered two other ways to scale. One is post-training scaling. Of course, t=
he first generation of post-training was reinforcement learning human feedb=
ack, but now we have reinforcement learning AI feedback and all forms of sy=
nthetic data generated data that assists in post-training scaling.

And one of the biggest events and one of the most exciting developments is =
Strawberry, ChatGPT o1, OpenAI=E2=80=99s o1, which does inference time scal=
ing, what=E2=80=99s called test time scaling. The longer it thinks, the bet=
ter and higher-quality answer it produces and it considers approaches like =
chain of thought and multi-path planning and all kinds of techniques necess=
ary to reflect and so on and so forth and it=E2=80=99s intuitively, it=E2=
=80=99s a little bit like us doing thinking in our head before we answer a =
question. And so we now have three ways of scaling and we=E2=80=99re seeing=
 all three ways of scaling. And as a result of that, the demand for our inf=
rastructure is really great.

It is certainly true that o1 type models are very good for Nvidia; raising =
inference-scaling laws, however, does not really answer the question about =
whether or not pre-training scaling has hit a wall. If it has, it is almost=
 certainly due to a lack of additional data; to that end, it=E2=80=99s unsu=
rprising that Huang also highlighted the potential of video content:

In the area of foundation model, now we have multimodality foundation model=
s and the amount of petabytes of video that these foundation models are goi=
ng to be trained on is incredible. And so my expectation is that for the fo=
reseeable future, we=E2=80=99re going to be scaling pre-training, post-trai=
ning as well as inference time scaling and which is the reason why I think =
we=E2=80=99re going to need more and more compute and we=E2=80=99re going t=
o have to drive as hard as we can to keep increasing the performance by X f=
actors at a time so that we can continue to drive down the cost and continu=
e to increase their revenues and get the AI revolution going.

I agree with Huang that video content may be the answer to any data wall th=
at exists (and, I would add, would be a big advantage for Google given that=
 they own YouTube); at the same time, this is an aspect of future Nvidia gr=
owth that is out of the company=E2=80=99s control.

The Networking Question
-----------------------

Meanwhile, a lot of folks noted the decline in Nvidia=E2=80=99s networking =
business:

( https://twitter.com/dylan522p/status/1859377972005700052?ref_src=3Dtwsrc%=
5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1859377972005700052%7Ctwgr%5E1f9ad51=
9d8c83e4827ef5ad67428b656de64a8c8%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&ref_url=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Fchro=
me-headless.local%3A9222%2Fatomic )

Kress was asked about the sequential decline in Nvidia=E2=80=99s networking=
 business:

Let=E2=80=99s first start with the networking. The growth year-over-year is=
 tremendous and our focus since the beginning of our acquisition of Mellano=
x has really been about building together the work that we do in terms of t=
he Data Center. The networking is such a critical part of that. Our ability=
 to sell our networking with many of our systems that we are doing in data =
center is continuing to grow and do quite well. So this quarter is just a s=
light dip down and we=E2=80=99re going to be right back up in terms of grow=
ing. They=E2=80=99re getting ready for Blackwell and more and more systems =
that will be using not only our existing networking but also the networking=
 that is going to be incorporated in a lot of these large systems that we a=
re providing them to.

O=E2=80=99Laughlin theorized that the decline was due to a delay in data ce=
nters coming online:

This quarter, China and Singapore were almost as large as the US. This easi=
ly could be a reason for a lower attach rate, as H20s and H100s that find t=
heir way to China often don=E2=80=99t come with Nvidia networking.

Nvidia's growing China/Singapore sales ( https://www.fabricatedknowledge.co=
m/p/nvidia-waiting-on-blackwell-and-whats )

This probably is a near-term headwind, but I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=
=99s the whole story. The entire story is that the power bottleneck is star=
ting to appear in Nvidia=E2=80=99s results. Let me explain.

On callbacks, it=E2=80=99s pretty clear that Nvidia thinks this is a timing=
 issue, not a real market share issue. Maybe they are losing share to Ether=
net, but I don=E2=80=99t think we=E2=80=99d see it this drastically. They a=
lso highlighted Spectrum-X on the call. Also, where would the hockey stick =
market share gain elsewhere if this was happening? The reality is much simp=
ler.

Networking is purchased last in a cluster=E2=80=99s purchase order, and rig=
ht now, datacenters are limiting GPU shipments. Microsoft talked about this=
 in their entire call, and now, with Nvidia=E2=80=99s result, I think the n=
etworking revenue will resolve itself over time. I do believe that Ethernet=
 and non-Infiniband are a real threat, but I don=E2=80=99t think 11% is the=
 number that will persist into the future. This is a reflection of bottlene=
cks.

I think that=E2=80=99s a valid thesis, but I have another one as well (that=
 doesn=E2=80=99t necessary contradict O=E2=80=99Laughlin, but may be in add=
ition to): specifically, I noted above that Kress said that Blackwell deman=
d exceeded supply, but didn=E2=80=99t say the same about Hopper. That makes=
 sense: there is a wait for the newest chips that are ramping up, while Hop=
per is already ramped and much more readily available.

Here=E2=80=99s the thing: as long as demand exceeds supply, Nvidia gets to =
pick-and-choose who it sells to, and the company prioritizes companies and =
build-outs that incorporate their networking. That means that the neoclouds=
 like CoreWeave get systems first, along with hyperscalers like Oracle and =
Azure that will install systems according to Nvidia=E2=80=99s specification=
s; other hyperscalers like Amazon, which want to use their own networking, =
get a much smaller allocation.

To that end, this last quarter didn=E2=80=99t see any material Blackwell sa=
les, because of the delay in shipment, which, by extension, means there was=
 no networking sales to go along with prioritized allocations; Hopper, mean=
while, was much more readily available, which means that companies who want=
 to use their own networking made up a much larger portion of Nvidia=E2=80=
=99s sales. That=E2=80=99s how you get a quarter with record revenue but se=
quential networking declines; by extension, a ramp in Blackwell should mean=
 a big jump up in Nvidia=E2=80=99s networking sales.

